277
00:14:21,380 --> 00:14:23,380
So I'm going to just go
ahead and take that off.

278
00:14:23,380 --> 00:14:26,280
All right.

279
00:14:26,280 --> 00:14:30,120
The second way that I wanted to
share with you on how to connect

280
00:14:30,120 --> 00:14:32,080
to data is through a join.

281
00:14:32,080 --> 00:14:36,160
And joins are more static
ways to combine data.

282
00:14:36,160 --> 00:14:41,080
They have physical tables
that must be defined.

283
00:14:41,080 --> 00:14:42,840
They're done before analysis.

284
00:14:42,840 --> 00:14:46,080
And they can't be changed
without impacting all the sheets

285
00:14:46,080 --> 00:14:47,420
using that data source.

286
00:14:47,420 --> 00:14:50,120
So it really does constrain you.

287
00:14:50,120 --> 00:14:55,160
Whereas a relationship can
provide as much available data

288
00:14:55,160 --> 00:14:56,640
to you as possible.

289
00:14:56,640 --> 00:15:00,460
There are times when you need to
join data for various reasons.

290
00:15:00,460 --> 00:15:03,520
Sometimes it's through
security reasons and so forth.

291
00:15:03,520 --> 00:15:08,360
But join tables are always
merged into a single table.

292
00:15:08,360 --> 00:15:13,000
So sometimes you will find that
there's unmatched values or even

293
00:15:13,000 --> 00:15:15,940
duplicates of the
aggregated values.

294
00:15:15,940 --> 00:15:17,560
And so that's some
of the problems

295
00:15:17,560 --> 00:15:21,308
that you might have to do some
more cleansing when you join.

296
00:15:21,308 --> 00:15:23,600
But like I said, I think the
primary reason for joining

297
00:15:23,600 --> 00:15:27,080
comes with security if I
need to hide a customer name

298
00:15:27,080 --> 00:15:30,320
and I've got a specific
ID and I need to match

299
00:15:30,320 --> 00:15:32,540
that with another table.

300
00:15:32,540 --> 00:15:37,920
So let's look at some of
the reasons why joins work

301
00:15:37,920 --> 00:15:40,520
or what to expect
when you see joins.

302
00:15:40,520 --> 00:15:44,330
They are displayed with a
Venn diagram icons so that you

303
00:15:44,330 --> 00:15:48,050
can see, oh, this is a join.

304
00:15:48,050 --> 00:15:51,970
It does require you to select
join types and to join clauses.

305
00:15:51,970 --> 00:15:55,250
You can join physical tables
as are merged together

306
00:15:55,250 --> 00:15:58,490
into a single logical
table, but with a fixed

307
00:15:58,490 --> 00:16:00,330
combination of data.

308
00:16:00,330 --> 00:16:04,710
You, during the join, may
drop unmatched measure values.

309
00:16:04,710 --> 00:16:08,290
And of course, you may
duplicate aggregate values

310
00:16:08,290 --> 00:16:11,210
when fields are at
different levels of detail.

311
00:16:11,210 --> 00:16:13,810
And it does support
scenarios that

312
00:16:13,810 --> 00:16:17,230
require a single table of data,
such as an extract, filter,

313
00:16:17,230 --> 00:16:18,510
and aggregation.

314
00:16:18,510 --> 00:16:22,750
So that's another pro maybe
for an advanced feature.

315
00:16:22,750 --> 00:16:24,070
So there are some good things.

316
00:16:24,070 --> 00:16:26,670
Most of the time, you will
be using relationships.

317
00:16:26,670 --> 00:16:29,330
But let's go ahead and
